layouts.CourseName: Smugglers Notch Disc Golf Center - Brewster Ridge
layouts.Name: 2024 DGPT Playoffs: GMC Brewster MPO
layouts.Notes:
• 2-METER RULE: The 2-meter rule is not in effect.
• COURSE MARKINGS: Areas of the course will be marked in colored paint as follows: OB lines will be marked in WHITE paint; HAZARD lines will be YELLOW; MANDATORY LINES and DROP ZONES will be marked in ORANGE; Dened CASUAL areas will be marked in RED; RELIEF areas will be marked in PINK; 
Areas designated to be of SAFETY concern will be marked in BRIGHT GREEN.
• OUT OF BOUNDS: OB areas (including water) are primarily designated by a white painted line or white fabric strap/rope. Where present, white OB stakes may be used as a visual aid. Where fencing is used, the bottom of the fence is the line. As is standard, the line itself is considered OB. (806.02)
• CASUAL WATER: Players may obtain relief from unmarked casual water per PDGA Rule 806.03.
• AD WALLS: Ad walls that are parallel to an OB line DO NOT serve as the OB line. The OB line will be designated by a painted line running in front of and parallel to the walls. The minimum distance between the walls and OB line is 1 meter.
• DROP ZONES: Drop Zones (DZ) are provided on several holes for certain shots that come to rest OB. Unless otherwise specified, players may re-throw from their previous lie (tee), from where the disc was last in-bounds, OR from the Drop Zone. One penalty throw is assessed no matter which option is chosen.
• RELIEF FROM OBSTACLES: Players may obtain relief backward on the line of play, without penalty, from temporarily placed advertising assets, permanent sign posts, fairway markers, gopher holes, golf course utility boxes (green plastic fixtures), per PDGA Rule 803.02 (A). As the rule states, ‘’unless greater relief is announced by the Director’’ instead of only taking the closest lie that provides relief, the Tournament Director has granted up to 1 m relief from the aforementioned assets/obstacles.
• CASUAL OBSTACLES: Per rule 803.01 (B) (1), “A casual obstacle is ... any item as designated by the Director,” spectator stakes and ropes that are in-bounds have been designated as casual obstacles, and may be moved and replaced ONLY if they impede a player’s stance.
• RELIEF AREAS: Any active wildlife dens or insect nests will be marked and played as RELIEF AREAS. These areas may be added or removed during the event based on wild-life or insect activity. If an area is marked at the beginning of a round it will remain marked for the entire round. PDGA Rule 806.04 “...A relief area is played as an out-of-bounds area with the exception that no penalty throw is assessed to a player whose disc comes to rest in a relief area.’’
• PLAYER GUESTS: Per PDGA waiver, players are responsible for friends or family who are spectators and who attempt to join the playing group in violation of CM 3.05.G. Players will receive courtesy violation penalties under 812.C if this occurs.
